Title: An Analysis of Information Content in Standardized vs. Specialized Multinational Advertisements
Pages: 23-39
Author-Name: Barbara Mueller
Author-Workplace-Name: San Diego State University
File-URL: http://www.palgrave-journals.com/jibs/journal/v22/n1/pdf/8490290a.pdf
File-Format: Application/pdf
File-Function: Link to full text PDF
File-URL: http://www.palgrave-journals.com/jibs/journal/v22/n1/full/8490290a.html
File-Format: text/html
File-Function: Link to full text HTML
Abstract: Print and television advertisements for a variety of American products appearing in the U.S., Germany and Japan are analyzed to explore differences in the informational content of standardized vs. specialized approaches to multinational advertising. Overall, highly standardized messages were found to contain significantly fewer consumer information cues than highly specialized messages. This trend was found to hold true, regardless of product category. The more standardized the message being transferred, whether for a high or low involvement purchase item, the lower the level of consumer information contained within the commercial message.&copy; 1991 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1991) 22, 23&ndash;39
